<div class="content">
      <p>
          During my undergraduate art program, I focused a lot on identity and how technology plays a role in 
          forming our physical identities, not just our online identities. Over the course of my Masters program 
          at MCAD, I have shifted my focus towards how the overuse of technology impacts our relationships, 
          both with ourselves in shaping our identities, and our relationships with others. <br><br>

          When I began creating MESH, I really wanted the name of the project to have roots in technology itself, 
          and technology’s relationship to humans. I began thinking about how humans network with each other, and 
          also the idea of computer networking. It struck me that this network pattern exists in many places. 
          The massive and completely invisible infrastructure of wireless networking really fascinates me, so I 
          started investigating recent advancements in wireless networking. One such advancement is the mesh wireless 
          network. A mesh network is a network of wireless routers that create a highly reliable connection for a 
          large area, like an entire home or office space. Companies like Eero and Google, among others, are producing 
          and selling these mesh network setups to consumers. This type of wireless network intrigued me because it 
          seemed to mirror, or actualize, the same pattern that human networks have. Our relationships and communities 
          are built on these webs of connectedness.
      </p>
    </div>



    Project MESH is a space to build community and dialogue around the topic of humans’ relationship
          to technology. I hope to highlight and deepen the benefits of technology in our relationships
          and encourage awareness and mindfulness of the drawbacks, in order to ultimately strengthen our
          relationships with each other, as humans. Moving forward, I hope to produce more volumes of
          the MESH zine, encourage more people to submit work and join the conversation, and eventually
          use the ideas behind Project MESH to create an in-person interactive installation.